\section{Introduction}
In recent years we have seen exponential increase in the field of robotics and autonomous machinery. Robots are more capable of performing fine motor movement with each passing year such as opening doors, navigating stairs and even back flips. Taking this to the logical end point, when the machines eventually try to lobotomize the human race, one might ask the question ``What is the effect of High energy particles on complex machinery designed to mimic the human anatomy''? In this report we hope to explore this exact question and others such as

\begin{itemize}
\item What is the cut off energy to conceivably short circuit/kill an android?
\item which energies consistently produce this cut off energy? (Higher energies cause the production of more secondary particles which also contribute to the energy deposition)
\item Why... did i even choose this topic
\end{itemize}

In short, we are testing what kind of particles we need in certain energy ranges to deposit sufficient energy to destroy modern day electronics/robotics. We will be approximating the chemical composition of future machinery to current machinery and testing against known values of currents/energies deposited that cause machinery to fail. The skeletal shape of the robots also plays an important factor as the primary surface area for destruction will be the robots chest and head (Where most the vital components are stored) as opposed to the same test on just a computer which we could approximate to a cube where the entire cube is the surface area of destruction.

This report will be made up of the following sections: ``\textbf{The Problem}'' where we will be discussing the physics, approximations and relevance (if any) of what we are studying. ``\textbf{Method}'' How Geant4 can be used to simulate our conundrum and acquire relevant data. ``\textbf{Description}'' The step by step process of how the simulation was undertaken inside Geant4 and what occurred. ``\textbf{Results and Conclusion}'' self explanatory.

Introductions over, time to annihilate robots of all possible genders.

\newpage
\section{The Problem}
\subsection{Background Physics}

Energized particles do damage to electronics via ionization . The amount of damage is heavily dependent on the distance from target to source, energy of the particle, number of particles and the composition of material being penetrated \cite{thesis}. For instance if the robots where wearing a protective layer of lead of about a few cm's thick then we would need much higher energy particles to penetrate this barrier due to leads high attenuation attributed to it's high density. For this project however we will make the assumption that this is not the case based on the fact that due to leads high density, a protective coating of lead would weigh a considerable amount and restrict the robots movement as to allow us to batter them with sticks or some other pointy objects.

We may also assume nothing lies in the path of us and the target i.e the density of the medium between source and target will be negligible. So to summarize: we will consider a beam of energized particles towards a target at a distance of a few metres away in a low density medium (i.e air). The attenuation considered will come solely from the composition of the robot and no other external sources.

Consider the case of gamma ray's which have an energy ranging from $\approx$100KeV to as high as 10TeV interacting with the electrical components \cite{wikipedia}. Gamma-ray photons deposit their energy via ionization where the bulk of this damage comes from the enhancement of conductivity via the creation of extra charge carriers and trapped charge \cite{radiation}. These photons interact in the following ways \cite{matter}:
\begin{itemize}
\item Photoelectric effect
\item Compton effect
\item Electron-positron pair production
\end{itemize}
The later two process's occur for high-energy photons which will be the case we will consider. These effects cause the conductivity to be of the material to be enhanced  \cite{thesis}. In silicon based compounds which is a primary chemical is processing chips \cite{chips}, the energy needed to create an electron positron pair is given in Table \ref{table:1}:

\begin{table}[h!]
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|r|c|l|}
  \hline
  Material & $E_{ion}$[eV] \\
  \hline \hline
  Silicon & 3.6\\ 
  Silicon Dioxide & 18 \\
  \hline
  
\end{tabular}
\caption{The ionisation energy of silicon and silica \cite{silicon}}
\label{table:1}
\end{center}
\end{table}

We will assume that the vital components of the robots are comprised of silicon based compounds similar to modern processing chips. Without going into the nitty gritty detail, these effects all contribute to the failure of electrical components. Where all these are caused from high energy photons depositing their energy which is the main statistic we will be sampling i.e the energy deposited and where.

The minimum energy required to cause damage to the electrical components is 10MeV (this figure is based on the energies of particles in the Van Allen belts which cause issues for satellites \cite{radiation}). We will take the approximate of 10MeV and claim this as our damage cut off based on the fact that the energy required to make electron positron pairs is only 3.6eV in our silicon processors (i.e when 10MeV is deposited into the material we will consider it destroyed). Taking this into account we wish to calculate two things, the minimum energy required for the particle to deposit the cut off energy into the robots vulnerable areas and the percentage of particles that successfully deposit the cut off energy into the robots vulnerable bits per 50 particles (where clearly for the later statement each trial will have 50 particles with energy greater or equal to the minimum energy needed to produce successful destruction).

\subsection{Robot Composition and Construction}
Due to the primary area of surface destruction being the head and chest, we will assume that all vital electrical components will be contained under the rib cage as this allows for the most defence against radiation. We will keep two lungs as targets for our particle beams and remove all other organs (expect the testicles which must stay).

The remaining organs (the lungs) will act as our primary target i.e when 10MeV is deposited into either lung we will consider this robot obliterated. There is a case to be made that the head which will contain all the robots visual sensory information is also of importance for extermination (assuming that future robots are still narcissistically made in our image). However we may assume that at best this will cripple the robots visual feeds so we will stick to extermination.

The robots will be composed of two materials, one for the skeleton and one for the head and organs/gizmos. The skeleton was chosen to be composed of grade 5 titanium alloy which contains 6\% aluminum, 4\% vanadium, 0.25\% iron, 0.2\% oxygen and the remainder being titanium with a density of 4.43*g/cm3. This is the most commonly used titanium alloy and boasts adequate strength for our purposes  \cite{titanium}. The rest will be composed of stainless steel 316 which contains 12\% Nickel, 17\% Chromium, 2.5\% Molybdenum, 1\% silicon, 2\% Manganese, 0.08\% Copper, 0.045\% Phosphorus, 0.03\% Sulfur with the remainder being iron with a density of 8.03*g/cm3 \cite{steel}.

\subsection{Results Applications}
Whilst the original goal of this report was for the own creators amusement we may extrapolate its results to apply for modern day robotics. For instance with the advance of technology it is highly likely that more complex machinery will be used to survey outer planets such as mars which has a thinner atmosphere. Understanding how high energy particles interact with electronics will be vital in damage prevention and maintenance of the machinery. Particularly prevention in the case of planetary expeditions where maintenance will not be an option. One must also consider that during the journey to for instance Mars, the absence of an atmosphere will pose problems for on board electronics. Essentially we can extend the results of this analysis to any case where electronics are being used in the absence of protection (i.e. an atmosphere).

