\section{Method}
Geant4 already contains a majority of the physics processes we will be testing for (production of secondary particles from collisions, sensor/detector that records the energy deposition and relevant particle dynamics i.e Compton scattering etc.).

\subsection{Robot Creation}
For our project we will be editing the pre-existing Geant4 example human phantom to meet our specified parameters for a generic robot and using Geant4's inbuilt beam function to fire high energy particles at our target. Firstly we must add the new elements our robots are composed of to the file ``G4HumanPhantomMaterial.cc'' which contains an element list plus the compositions of human skin, skeletal system, organs etc. Below is an example of defining the element Aluminum:

\begin{figure}[H]
    \begin{center}
      \includegraphics[width=12cm,height=1.5cm]{Image_1}
      \caption{Declaration of Aluminum}
    \end{center}
  \end{figure}

where $Z$ is the atomic number and $A$ the molar mass. Following this process we include elements such as Titanium, Cobalt, Nickel and other various metals where their values for atomic number and molar mass come from the periodic table \cite{periodic}. 

\begin{figure}[H]
    \begin{center}
      \includegraphics[width=8cm,height=7cm]{Image_2}
      \caption{Declaration of Titanium Alloy and stainless steel}
    \end{center}
  \end{figure}

Next we construct the titanium alloy and stainless steel compounds using the Geant4 function ``G4Material'' shown above.  Where in this declaration $d$ is the density and the element is defined under the following syntax:
  \[\text{G4Material(Name, density value, Number of elements)}\]
  Next we go into the file ``G4HumanPhantomConstruction.cc'' and comment out the construction of all organs expect the lungs (and testicles). Similarly we comment out setting the detectors sensitivity for these removed organs.

  \begin{figure}[H]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=.7\textwidth,height=.3\textwidth]{Image_4} 
        \caption{Commented out construction}
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth,height=.25\textwidth]{Image_5} 
        \caption{Commented out detector sensitivity}
  \end{figure}
      
  Finally this produces our test subject the T-2000 robot eviscerator. From here we will simply manually change the energy of the particle beam inside Geant4's GUI and fire the particles at our recipient. The beam is already set to gamma ray production and incorporates electron positron pair production.

\subsection{Data Collection Methods}
There are a few ways we could collect data and reach a conclusion for this experiment but we will just cover the following methods. Firstly we want to calculate the minimum energy of the particle beam required to deposit the cut off energy for one particle which is not 10MeV as one might naively think due to the protection/attenuation of the rib cage.

It is worth noting the relationship between the energy per particle and the number of particles required to reach the cut off however as we wish to draw a conclusion about economic viability of the following two approaches:
\begin{itemize}
\item Higher particle number, lower energy per particle
\item Lower particle number, Higher energy per particle
\end{itemize}
where the complications come from the inaccuracy of the particle beam. This is of importance to us due to the fact that lower energy particles are easier to produce so we wish to strike a balance between economic viability and efficiency.

A higher particle number beam has a lower probability of depositing all its energy into a medium then a lower particle number beam. This can be mathematically represented quite easily: suppose we consider the case where we want to deposit energy $E$ for $n$ particles. if the probability of a particle depositing it's energy is $P$ then the total probability of all particles depositing their energies is
\[P_{\text{T}}=P^n\]
where $0<P<1$ and $n\in\mathbb{N}$. The figure below shows a diagrammatic representation of this for the listed probabilities. 



