\section{Description}
\subsection{The Simulation}  
We begin by building our edited human phantom model in a directory of our choosing under the usual commands
\[\text{cmake -DCMAKE\_PREFIX\_PATH=$\sim$/Documents/geant4/geant4.10.04.p01-install}\]
\[\text{ $\sim$/Documents/geant4/examples/robot}\]
This creates the necessary build files and then we simply type
\[\text{make -j4}\]
to build our robot. Running our robot with the command $"./\text{phantom}"$ brings up the visualization and lets us see our overlord in all his glory.
\begin{wrapfigure}{r}{0.25\textwidth}
   \centering
      \includegraphics[width=.2\textwidth,height=.5\textwidth]{Image_3}
      \caption{Machine Overlord}
  \end{wrapfigure}
  We now want to alter the inbuilt beam function to fire high energy particles at our newly constructed target and record the energy deposited. This process of altering the beams energy will be continued until we reach the minimum energy required to deposit the cut off energy of destruction which was recorded as 10MeV from our previous sources (note that this will be carried out with only one particle in the particle beam, more on this below).

  To alter the beams energy we input the following command into the GUI
  \[ \text{/gps/energy $\langle$ Energy $\rangle$ $\langle$ Unit $\rangle$ }   \]
  where units may be eV, MeV, GeV etc. After the beam energy is altered we then run the beam using
  \[ \text{ /run/beamOn $\langle$ nParticles $\rangle$} \]
  where nParticles=number of particles. This command will run our beam and output a list of organs with the energy deposition in each. After we achieve the minimum energy we re run the simulation with gradually increasing energy from this minimum for ten particles in the particle beam






























